INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("372", "1", "2015-06-16 04:58:18", "2015-06-16 04:58:18", "[caption id=\"attachment_365\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"299\"]<a href=\"http://sweetbabylilly.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/Baby-not-sleeping.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-365\" title=\"Baby not sleeping\" alt=\"Baby not sleeping\" src=\"http://sweetbabylilly.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/Baby-not-sleeping.jpg\" width=\"299\" height=\"168\" /></a> Is your baby not Sleeping?[/caption]\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\"> Is your baby not sleeping? There is nothing sweeter than a sleeping baby, but sometimes it may seem like all your baby wants to do is anything but sleep. According to the Australian Centre for Education in Sleep ( ACES), an Australian organisation founded to increase awareness about the importance of sleep and what happens when we don\'t get enough sleep, babies under 1 need  14-18 hours of sleep throughout the day and night. Healthy baby sleep is crucial to your baby’s brain development and decreases chances of general health problems and emotional difficulties like depression and anxiety later in life. Is your baby keeping you up all night, here are some good tips to give your baby and you, your sleep back.</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Routine. Having a routine before bed cues your baby that it is time to transition to bedtime. Keep a consistent bed time every night.  You can start a routine with a bath and story before bed.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Naps. Babies sleep better at night when they are taking consistent naps during the day. If a baby is too tired this in turn came make the transition to sleep even more difficult.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Environment. Create the best environment that is conducive to sleep for your baby.Make sure that the room is dark enough and is a comfortable sleeping environment. You can add a sound machine or a fan. White noise can help drown out other noises especially if you have other children who are older that like to run around.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Be Active During the Day. Keep your baby active and stimulated when they are awake. This will help them go down faster and longer. Take time to play with your baby. Not only does it help with their sleep but helps with the development as well.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Don’t put baby down with bottle. When establishing bedtime routines it is not good to put baby down with a last bottle. You may be thinking that they may sleep longer because they won’t wake up hungry but in turn they will probably wake up wanting their diaper changed.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Don’t bring baby in your bed. Both baby and you sleep better when you are in your own beds. It also helps with their separation anxiety and it is safer for baby to sleep alone.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Help ease the transition. When you put your baby to bed, stay with them for 10-15 minutes before leaving the room. This helps them transition better and helps get them more familiar with their surroundings before bed</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">If you are breastfeeding stop drinking caffeine. Caffeine from soda and coffee can turn up in your breast milk and it can be enough to affect your newborn. It is best to cut back on these drinks especially when you are nearing bedtime.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Regulate their bedroom temperature. Babies sleep better in a cooler room. The optimal temperature for a baby’s room is between 19 and 21 degrees Celsius. If you can’t regulate your child’s room, turn on a fan or open a window slightly. Just make sure the room doesn’t get too cold or too hot.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Don’t make eye contact. When getting up for night time feedings or to sooth them it is best to avoid eye contact. When a baby makes eye contact with you it will cue them to think that it is time to get up.</p>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Do you find your baby is not sleeping?  Did you apply some of these tips successfully or would you like to share your findings with other mums, <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/sweetbabylilly\">Like us on Facebook </a>to join the Sweet Baby Lilly community.</p>\r\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Sweet dreams everyone !</p>", "Baby not sleeping? Try these great tips", "", "inherit", "open", "open", "", "361-autosave-v1", "", "", "2015-06-16 04:58:18", "2015-06-16 04:58:18", "", "361", "http://sweetbabylilly.com.au/361-autosave-v1/", "0", "revision", "", "0");
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("374", "100", "2015-06-16 05:54:37", "2015-06-16 05:54:37", "<a href=\"http://sweetbabylilly.com.au/healthy-baby-sleep/\"> </a><a href=\"http://sweetbabylilly.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/Healthy-Baby-Sleep.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-325\" alt=\"Healthy Baby Sleep\" src=\"http://sweetbabylilly.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/Healthy-Baby-Sleep-300x199.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"199\" /></a>\r\n\r\nAs a mum I understand that taking good care of your baby is most certainly your top priority. When it comes to healthy baby sleep, safety precautions are just as essential as with anything else. According to Sids and Kids, an Australian organisation dedicated to research and prevention of Sudden Infant Death Syndrome (SIDS), approximately 120 Australian babies still die each year from SIDS. It is the leading cause of babies within their first years of age and experts have linked it to unaccustomed tummy sleeping. Ensure your baby’s healthy sleep by following our 5 safety tips:\r\n\r\n<span style=\"color: #000000;\"> </span>1.      Sleep position – always on the back\r\n\r\nIt’s best to put your baby to sleep on the back, rather than on the tummy or the side. Their risk of SIDS is higher, when they sleep on their tummies, as this position puts the baby’s face in the mattress, which can cause suffocation. You can also use a baby sleeping bag, as it will encourage the right sleeping position and will keep your baby safe.\r\n\r\n2.      Choose a firm bed and avoid toys\r\n\r\nAlways put your baby to sleep on a firm mattress with a fitted sheet or a baby sleeping bag. Avoid placing any blankets, quilts and pillows, as well as stuffed toys in your baby’s crib.\r\n\r\n3.      Prevent overheating\r\n\r\nMonitor your baby’s temperature at all times. Overheating increases the risk of SIDS, so make sure to choose light and comfortable sleeping clothes for your baby. To keep your baby warm, dress him or her in a onesie or use a baby sleeping bag.\r\n\r\n4.      Don’t sleep in the same bed as your baby\r\n\r\nTaking your new baby in your bed might seem like a good idea, but it can actually increase their risk of SIDS. Your blankets and pillows present a safety hazard to your baby’s health. In fact, the safest place for your baby is their own crib.\r\n\r\n5.      Keep their face and head uncovered\r\n\r\nUsing loose bedding can cover the face and head of your baby and increase their SIDS risk. If you’re using a baby sleeping bag, the absence of loose blankets will minimize the risk of SIDS. Always place your baby on their back and use firmly tucked in covers. When putting your baby to sleep, check if their feet are positioned at the bottom of the cot and remove any head coverings, such as hats.\r\n\r\nKeep your baby safe at night, and ensure healthy baby sleep. Baby sleeping bags are one of the safest sleeping clothing you can have for your baby. Sleeping bags from Sweet Baby Lilly are also low fire danger, an added safety benefit for your baby.\r\n\r\nPS. I have some beautiful baby sleeping bags available for boys and girls ... <a title=\"Sweet Baby Lilly Shop\" href=\"http://sweetbabylilly.com.au/shop/\">click here </a>to purchase yours today.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"color: #000000; font-family: Calibri; font-size: medium;\"> </span>", "5 Safety Tips for a Healthy Baby Sleep", "As a mum I understand that taking good care of your baby is most certainly your top priority. When it comes to healthy baby sleep, safety precautions are just as essential as with anything else. According to Sids and Kids, an Australian organisation dedicated to research and prevention of Sudden Infant Death Syndrome (SIDS),", "inherit", "open", "open", "", "299-revision-v1", "", "", "2015-06-16 05:54:37", "2015-06-16 05:54:37", "", "299", "http://sweetbabylilly.com.au/299-revision-v1/", "0", "revision", "", "0");
